<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n05038e"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n05" href="#n05038e">N05 (VI.B.2)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n05all.htm#n05038e"> 38(e)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> S. Clement (Rome)</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">He <font color="green">[Fr. Burke]</font> felt his mission strengthen while he traced in an unbroken chain the power the Church possessed from the day when the hands of Christ pressed upon the head of Peter. Not one link in that chain was wanting, he said. The Catholic preacher was sent by Pius, who was of Gregory, who was of Pius, who was of Leo&mdash;and so on until he came to <mark>Clement</mark>, who was of Cletus, who was of Linus, who was of Peter, who was of Christ, who was of God. <small> William J. Fitz-Patrick, <a name="BURKE" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#BURKE"><cite title="source">The Life of the Very Rev. Thomas N. Burke</cite></a>, (1885) I, 252f</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Clement or Clemens is the name of seventeen popes, of whom three, as schismatics, are not usually reckoned. The first <mark>Clemens Romanus</mark> was one of the Apostolic Fathers, and is reckoned variously as the second or third successor of Saint Peter in the see of Rome. </mm> </dd></dl>
